# Test Patterns

## Accessing internal functions in tests

The `$`-prefixed exposed contracts are **automatically generated** by [hardhat-exposed](https://github.com/frangio/hardhat-exposed). The plugin generates a `$ContractName` wrapper for every contract, with every internal `_function` re-exposed as an external `$_function`. These are emitted into `contracts-exposed/` (gitignored) and are available in tests without any manual work:

```javascript
const token = await ethers.deployContract('$ERC20', ['Name', 'SYM']);
await token.$_mint(holder, 1000n);
```

**Do not write `$`-prefixed wrapper contracts by hand.**

## Manual mocks in `contracts/mocks/`

Manual mocks are only written when the auto-generated exposed contract is not sufficient. `contracts/mocks/` mirrors the `contracts/` directory structure. Do not put mocks in `test/`.

Write a manual mock when you need:

- **Constructor-level setup** that auto-generation cannot provide (e.g. `ERC721ConsecutiveMock` which mints batches during construction using `_mintConsecutive`).
- **Multi-extension composition** to test the interaction of several extensions together (e.g. `ERC721ConsecutiveMock` combining `ERC721Consecutive + ERC721Pausable + ERC721Votes`).
- **Injected behavior** that overrides a hook to simulate edge cases (e.g. `ERC20Reentrant` which calls back into the token inside `_update`).
- **Adversarial or protocol-specific behavior** that has no analogue in the base contract (e.g. `ReentrancyAttack`, `ERC20ReturnFalseMock`).
- **A public entry point** for an internal operation that hardhat-exposed generates with the wrong signature or that requires additional logic (e.g. `ERC20Mock.mint` which is a plain `external` wrapper with no special setup needed).

Even within a manual mock, prefer calling the auto-generated `$_` functions over re-declaring an internal exposure:

```solidity
// prefer this (reuses auto-generated exposure):
await token.$_mint(holder, 1000n);

// avoid this (redundant re-declaration already handled by hardhat-exposed):
contract ERC20Mock is ERC20 {
    function $__mint(address account, uint256 value) external { _mint(account, value); }
}
```

## Hardhat + Chai tests (`.test.js`)

- Use `loadFixture` from `@nomicfoundation/hardhat-network-helpers` for setup. Define a `fixture` async function; call `loadFixture(fixture)` in `beforeEach`.
- Test structure: `describe('ContractName') > describe('methodName') > it('description')`
- Reuse behavior via `shouldBehaveLike*` functions in `.behavior.js` files.
- Custom errors: `.revertedWithCustomError(contract, 'ErrorName').withArgs(...)`
- Events: `.emit(contract, 'EventName').withArgs(...)`
- Use `bigint` literals (`100n`) for uint values: not `ethers.BigNumber`.

## Foundry tests (`.t.sol`) and formal verification

### When to use each approach

| Approach            | Required when                                                                              |
| ------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Formal verification | Contract includes a state machine or access control rules                                  |
| Fuzzing             | Math-heavy code, data structures, or complex invariants not suited for formal verification |
| Edge unit cases     | All high-risk contracts, unexpected/pathological inputs, border cases                      |

### Fuzzing with Foundry

Fuzz test functions take typed parameters directly and are run by Foundry automatically:

```solidity
function testFuzzAdd(uint256 a, uint256 b) public pure {
  // vm.assume(...) to restrict inputs if needed
  assertEq(Math.add(a, b), a + b);
}
```

Use `assertEq`, `assertGt`, etc. from `forge-std/Test.sol`.

### Formal verification: Halmos

[Halmos](https://github.com/a16z/halmos) runs symbolic execution directly on Foundry test files. Symbolic test functions must be prefixed with `symbolic` or `testSymbolic` — this is what the CI `halmos` job matches (`--match-test '^symbolic|^testSymbolic'`). These functions also run as regular fuzz tests under Foundry:

```solidity
function testSymbolicTransfer(address to, uint256 amount) public {
  // halmos treats inputs as fully symbolic (all possible values)
  // add vm.assume(...) for preconditions
}
```

Halmos runs on every PR. Prefer Halmos when the property can be expressed as a Foundry test — it is fast and requires no external tooling.

### Formal verification: Certora

[Certora](https://certora.com) is more powerful than Halmos for complex state machine rules and access control invariants. Specs live in `fv/specs/` as `.conf` + `.spec` file pairs. Certora runs on PRs labeled `formal-verification` or `formal-verification-force-all`. To run locally:

```bash
node fv/run.js AccessControl   # runs fv/specs/AccessControl.conf
node fv/run.js --all           # runs all specs
```

Before running, apply the harness patches:

```bash
make -C fv apply
```

Use Certora when a property is too complex for Halmos or when deeper rule coverage is needed. It requires a `CERTORAKEY`.

## Changeset format

Every PR that changes contract behavior needs a changeset. Generate one with:

```bash
npx changeset add
```

This creates a file in `.changeset/`. The format is:

```
---
'openzeppelin-solidity': minor
---

`ComponentName`: One-sentence description of what changed.
```

- `minor` for new features, `patch` for bug fixes.
- Description starts with a backtick-quoted contract/component name, followed by a single sentence. No bullet points, no multi-paragraph prose.
